I only want to include cases without missingness in this model: model <- glm(any_recid ~ spep_total, data = final_merged, family = binomial)
ChatGPT said:

To include only cases without missingness in your model, you can filter the dataset before running the model using na.omit() or by using the complete.cases() function. Here's how you can do it:

Method 1: Using na.omit()

r
model <- glm(any_recid ~ spep_total, data = na.omit(final_merged), family = binomial)

This method automatically removes any rows with missing data across all variables included in the dataset.

Method 2: Using complete.cases()

r
model <- glm(any_recid ~ spep_total, data = final_merged[complete.cases(final_merged$spep_total, final_merged$any_recid), ], family = binomial)

This method is more flexible, allowing you to specify which variables should be checked for missingness. It only includes rows where both spep_total and any_recid are not missing.

Both approaches ensure that the model only considers cases with complete data.

ChatGPT said:

You can loop through your independent variables and fit a logistic regression model for each one using glm(). Here's how you can automate this process in R:

r
# List of independent variables
iv_list <- c(
  "yls_total", "spep_total", "pop_score", "target_dosage", "target_duration", 
  "service_type", "points_received_primary_service_type", "points_received_quality_of_service_delivery", 
  "points_received_amount_of_service_duration", "points_received_amount_of_service_contact_hours", 
  "total_quality_measures_received", "quality_of_service_delivery", "total_pts_amount_of_service", 
  "total_pts_risk_level", "predicted_probability_score", "difference_score"
)

# Loop through each independent variable and fit a model
results <- lapply(iv_list, function(iv) {
  formula <- as.formula(paste("any_recid ~", iv))
  glm(formula, data = na.omit(final_merged), family = binomial)
})

# Print summaries for each model
lapply(results, summary)

How the Code Works:

  1. iv_list: Contains all your independent variables.
  2. lapply(): Iterates over each variable in iv_list, fitting a logistic regression model (glm()) with any_recid as the dependent variable.
  3. as.formula(): Dynamically creates the formula for each regression (e.g., any_recid ~ yls_total).
  4. na.omit(final_merged): Ensures that only complete cases are used for each regression.
  5. lapply(results, summary): Displays the summary of each fitted model.

You can customize this further if you want to save the coefficients, p-values, or any other specific output for later analysis.

can the estimate and pvalue for each be collated in a table?
ChatGPT said:

Certainly! You can extract the estimate and p-value for each independent variable and collate them into a table. Here's how you can do it:

r
# List of independent variables
iv_list <- c(
  "yls_total", "spep_total", "pop_score", "target_dosage", "target_duration", 
  "service_type", "points_received_primary_service_type", "points_received_quality_of_service_delivery", 
  "points_received_amount_of_service_duration", "points_received_amount_of_service_contact_hours", 
  "total_quality_measures_received", "quality_of_service_delivery", "total_pts_amount_of_service", 
  "total_pts_risk_level", "predicted_probability_score", "difference_score"
)

# Initialize an empty data frame to store the results
results_df <- data.frame(IV = character(), Estimate = numeric(), P_Value = numeric(), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Loop through each independent variable and fit a model
for (iv in iv_list) {
  formula <- as.formula(paste("any_recid ~", iv))
  model <- glm(formula, data = na.omit(final_merged), family = binomial)
  # Extract the coefficient (estimate) and p-value for the IV (ignoring the intercept)
  estimate <- summary(model)$coefficients[2, 1]
  p_value <- summary(model)$coefficients[2, 4]
  # Add the results to the data frame
  results_df <- rbind(results_df, data.frame(IV = iv, Estimate = estimate, P_Value = p_value))
}

# Display the table
print(results_df)

Explanation:

  1. results_df: An empty data frame is created to store the results.
  2. Loop: For each independent variable:
    • A logistic regression model is fit.
    • The estimate and p-value for the independent variable are extracted (ignoring the intercept).
    • The results are added to the data frame.
  3. summary(model)$coefficients[2, 1]: Extracts the estimate (coefficient) for the independent variable.
  4. summary(model)$coefficients[2, 4]: Extracts the p-value for the independent variable.
  5. rbind(): Adds the results to the data frame.

The final results_df table will show the independent variable, its estimate, and the corresponding p-value.

You said:
Can the effects be standardized? And can AUC's also be included in the table?
ChatGPT said:

Yes, you can standardize the effects and include AUC (Area Under the Curve) in the table. Standardizing the effects allows you to interpret the coefficients in terms of standard deviations, which is useful for comparing the relative importance of the predictors. The AUC gives you an idea of the model's classification performance.

Here’s how to do that:

  1. Standardizing the independent variables: We’ll standardize each IV by subtracting the mean and dividing by the standard deviation.
  2. Computing the AUC: We can use the pROC package to calculate the AUC for each model.

Here’s the full implementation:

r
# Required library for computing AUC
if (!require("pROC")) install.packages("pROC")
library(pROC)

# List of independent variables
iv_list <- c(
  "yls_total", "spep_total", "pop_score", "target_dosage", "target_duration", 
  "service_type", "points_received_primary_service_type", "points_received_quality_of_service_delivery", 
  "points_received_amount_of_service_duration", "points_received_amount_of_service_contact_hours", 
  "total_quality_measures_received", "quality_of_service_delivery", "total_pts_amount_of_service", 
  "total_pts_risk_level", "predicted_probability_score", "difference_score"
)

# Initialize an empty data frame to store the results
results_df <- data.frame(IV = character(), Estimate = numeric(), P_Value = numeric(), AUC = numeric(), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Loop through each independent variable and fit a model
for (iv in iv_list) {
  # Standardize the independent variable
  final_merged[[iv]] <- scale(final_merged[[iv]])
  
  # Create the formula and fit the logistic regression model
  formula <- as.formula(paste("any_recid ~", iv))
  model <- glm(formula, data = na.omit(final_merged), family = binomial)
  
  # Extract the coefficient (estimate) and p-value for the standardized IV
  estimate <- summary(model)$coefficients[2, 1]
  p_value <- summary(model)$coefficients[2, 4]
  
  # Calculate AUC
  roc_obj <- roc(na.omit(final_merged)$any_recid, fitted(model))
  auc_value <- auc(roc_obj)
  
  # Add the results to the data frame
  results_df <- rbind(results_df, data.frame(IV = iv, Estimate = estimate, P_Value = p_value, AUC = auc_value))
}

# Display the table
print(results_df)

Explanation:

  1. Standardization: The independent variable is standardized using scale(), which centers it to a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1.
  2. Logistic Regression: The model is fit using the standardized independent variable.
  3. Estimate and p-value: Extracted from the model as before.
  4. AUC Calculation: The AUC is computed using the roc() and auc() functions from the pROC package.
  5. Results Table: The table now includes the independent variable, standardized estimate, p-value, and AUC.

This process gives you a complete table with standardized effects and AUCs for each model, which allows you to compare both the relative importance and predictive performance of your variables.

ChatGPT said:

To include a random effect for unique_id, you need to use a mixed-effects logistic regression model instead of a simple glm() model. The lme4 package provides the glmer() function, which supports random effects. Here's how to modify your code:

  1. Install and load the lme4 package.
  2. Use glmer() instead of glm() to include a random effect.

Here’s how you can implement this:

r
# Required libraries
if (!require("pROC")) install.packages("pROC")
if (!require("lme4")) install.packages("lme4")
library(pROC)
library(lme4)

# List of independent variables
iv_list <- c(
  "yls_total", "spep_total", "pop_score", "target_dosage", "target_duration", "points_received_primary_service_type", 
  "points_received_quality_of_service_delivery", "points_received_amount_of_service_duration", 
  "points_received_amount_of_service_contact_hours", "total_quality_measures_received", "total_pts_amount_of_service", 
  "total_pts_risk_level", "predicted_probability_score", "difference_score"
)

# Initialize an empty data frame to store the results
results_df <- data.frame(IV = character(), Estimate = numeric(), P_Value = numeric(), AUC = numeric(), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Loop through each independent variable and fit a model with a random effect for unique_id
for (iv in iv_list) {
  # Standardize the independent variable
  final_merged[[iv]] <- scale(final_merged[[iv]])
  
  # Create the formula and fit the mixed-effects logistic regression model
  formula <- as.formula(paste("any_recid ~", iv, "+ (1 | unique_id)"))
  model <- glmer(formula, data = na.omit(final_merged), family = binomial)
  
  # Extract the coefficient (estimate) and p-value for the standardized IV
  estimate <- summary(model)$coefficients[2, 1]
  p_value <- summary(model)$coefficients[2, 4]
  
  # Calculate AUC
  roc_obj <- roc(na.omit(final_merged)$any_recid, fitted(model))
  auc_value <- auc(roc_obj)
  
  # Add the results to the data frame
  results_df <- rbind(results_df, data.frame(IV = iv, Estimate = estimate, P_Value = p_value, AUC = auc_value))
}

# Display the table
print(results_df)

Explanation:

  1. glmer(): This function from the lme4 package is used to fit a generalized linear mixed-effects model, allowing for the inclusion of random effects.
  2. Formula Specification: The formula now includes a random intercept for unique_id ((1 | unique_id)).
  3. Model Fitting: The process is similar to the glm() approach, but with the added complexity of random effects.
  4. AUC Calculation: The AUC is still calculated using pROC as before.

This setup will give you a table of standardized estimates, p-values, and AUCs while accounting for the random effect of unique_id. If you have any additional questions, feel free to ask!

You said:
all of the auc's are .99. Does it complicate calculating an AUC if the model includes random effects?
ChatGPT said:

Yes, including random effects in a model can complicate calculating the AUC. The reason is that mixed-effects models (like those produced by glmer()) generate predictions that reflect both fixed effects and random effects, which can lead to overly optimistic or misleadingly high AUC values, especially if the random effects are large.

In models with random effects, predictions are made for each subject or group (e.g., each unique_id), which can lead to near-perfect discrimination (hence the AUCs close to 0.99). However, this doesn’t necessarily reflect the true generalizability of the model; instead, it reflects how well the model fits the specific groups or individuals included in the training data.

Options for Handling AUC Calculation with Random Effects

  1. Use Marginal Predictions (Fixed Effects Only): You can calculate the AUC based only on the fixed effects (ignoring the random effects), which provides a better reflection of how well the model generalizes across new data points. Here’s how you can do it:

    r
    # Calculate AUC using only fixed effects
fixed_effects <- predict(model, type = "response", re.form = NA)
roc_obj <- roc(na.omit(final_merged)$any_recid, fixed_effects)
auc_value <- auc(roc_obj)

    The argument re.form = NA ensures that predictions are made using only the fixed effects.

  2. Cross-Validation: Perform cross-validation by fitting the model on different subsets of your data and calculating the AUC on hold-out samples. This approach can better account for overfitting due to random effects.

  3. Evaluate AUC at the Population Level: Instead of focusing on subject-specific AUCs, you can aggregate predictions across subjects or groups to calculate a population-level AUC.

Updated Code Example with Marginal AUC Calculation

r
# Required libraries
if (!require("pROC")) install.packages("pROC")
if (!require("lme4")) install.packages("lme4")
library(pROC)

  "points_received_amount_of_service_contact_hours", "total_quality_measures_received", "total_pts_amount_of_service", 
  "total_pts_risk_level", "predicted_probability_score", "difference_score"
)

# Initialize an empty data frame to store the results
results_df <- data.frame(IV = character(), Estimate = numeric(), P_Value = numeric(), AUC = numeric(), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Loop through each independent variable and fit a model with a random effect for unique_id

  # Standardize the independent variable
  final_merged[[iv]] <- scale(final_merged[[iv]])
  
  # Create the formula and fit the mixed-effects logistic regression model
  formula <- as.formula(paste("any_recid ~", iv, "+ (1 | unique_id)"))
  model <- glmer(formula, data = na.omit(final_merged), family = binomial)
  
  # Extract the coefficient (estimate) and p-value for the standardized IV
  estimate <- summary(model)$coefficients[2, 1]
  p_value <- summary(model)$coefficients[2, 4]
  
  # Calculate AUC using only fixed effects
  fixed_effects <- predict(model, type = "response", re.form = NA)
  roc_obj <- roc(na.omit(final_merged)$any_recid, fixed_effects)
  auc_value <- auc(roc_obj)

}

# Display the table

Key Points

  • Marginal AUC (fixed effects only) is typically more meaningful when assessing overall model performance, especially with random effects.
  • Random effects tend to overfit predictions to individual-level data, inflating the AUC.
  • Cross-validation or population-level evaluations can further improve the robustness of your AUC estimates.

This updated approach should yield more realistic AUC values for your models.

You said:
Can I standardize my ivs before inclduing them in a regression model?
ChatGPT said:

Yes, you can and should standardize your independent variables (IVs) before including them in a regression model, especially when dealing with mixed-effects models or when your IVs are on different scales. Standardization makes the regression coefficients more interpretable by expressing them in units of standard deviations, which allows for easier comparison across variables.

How to Standardize IVs Before Including Them in a Model

You can standardize your IVs by scaling them to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1 using the scale() function. Here’s how you can do it:

  1. Standardize Each IV: Use scale() to standardize your IVs before fitting them into the model.
  2. Include the Standardized IVs in the Model: Use the standardized variables directly in your regression model.

Example with Mixed-Effects Logistic Regression

r
# Required libraries
if (!require("pROC")) install.packages("pROC")
if (!require("lme4")) install.packages("lme4")
library(pROC)
library(lme4)

# List of independent variables
iv_list <- c(
  "yls_total", "spep_total", "pop_score", "target_dosage", "target_duration", "points_received_primary_service_type", 
  "points_received_quality_of_service_delivery", "points_received_amount_of_service_duration", 
  "points_received_amount_of_service_contact_hours", "total_quality_measures_received", "total_pts_amount_of_service", 
  "total_pts_risk_level", "predicted_probability_score", "difference_score"
)

# Standardize the IVs in the dataset
final_merged[iv_list] <- lapply(final_merged[iv_list], scale)

# Initialize an empty data frame to store the results
results_df <- data.frame(IV = character(), Estimate = numeric(), P_Value = numeric(), AUC = numeric(), stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# Loop through each independent variable and fit a model with a random effect for unique_id
for (iv in iv_list) {
  # Create the formula and fit the mixed-effects logistic regression model
  formula <- as.formula(paste("any_recid ~", iv, "+ (1 | unique_id)"))
  model <- glmer(formula, data = na.omit(final_merged), family = binomial)
  
  # Extract the coefficient (estimate) and p-value for the standardized IV
  estimate <- summary(model)$coefficients[2, 1]
  p_value <- summary(model)$coefficients[2, 4]
  
  # Calculate AUC using only fixed effects
  fixed_effects <- predict(model, type = "response", re.form = NA)
  roc_obj <- roc(na.omit(final_merged)$any_recid, fixed_effects)
  auc_value <- auc(roc_obj)
  
  # Add the results to the data frame
  results_df <- rbind(results_df, data.frame(IV = iv, Estimate = estimate, P_Value = p_value, AUC = auc_value))
}

# Display the table
print(results_df)

Key Points:

  • scale(): Standardizes the variables by centering them to a mean of 0 and scaling them to a standard deviation of 1.
  • Standardization Before Fitting: By standardizing the IVs before fitting the model, your regression coefficients will be directly interpretable as the effect of a one standard deviation change in the IV on the log-odds of the outcome.
  • Consistency: Standardizing before fitting also helps when comparing the effects across different IVs in your model.

Advantages of Standardizing:

  • Interpretability: The coefficients become comparable across variables.
  • Stability: Models can converge more reliably when predictors are on the same scale.

This approach should yield more meaningful results, especially when working with IVs that have different units or magnitudes.

library(lme4)

# List of independent variables
iv_list <- c(
  "yls_total", "spep_total", "pop_score", "target_dosage", "target_duration", "points_received_primary_service_type", 
  "points_received_quality_of_service_delivery", "points_received_amount_of_service_duration",

  3. Looping Through IVs: The loop runs the model for each IV and stores the estimates and p-values in a table for easy comparison.

How can I keep the side navigation drop downs closed initially?
ChatGPT said:

To keep the side navigation dropdowns (like the table of contents or navigation links) closed initially in your Nuxt 3 project, you need to manage the state of these dropdowns. Here’s an approach using Vue’s ref to control the open/closed state of each dropdown.

Approach:

  1. Use ref to store the open/closed state of each dropdown.
  2. Set the initial state to false (closed).
  3. Bind this state to the visibility of the dropdown content.

Example Implementation:

Let’s assume you have a sidebar component where dropdowns exist for each section:

Sidebar Component Example:

vue
<template>
  <nav>
    <ul>
      <li v-for="(section, index) in sections" :key="index">
        <button @click="toggleSection(index)">
          {{ section.title }}
        </button>
        <ul v-if="openSections[index]">
          <li v-for="item in section.items" :key="item">{{ item }}</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </nav>
</template>

<script setup lang="ts">
import { ref } from 'vue'

// Sample data for sidebar sections
const sections = [
  { title: 'Section 1', items: ['Item 1', 'Item 2'] },
  { title: 'Section 2', items: ['Item 3', 'Item 4'] },
  { title: 'Section 3', items: ['Item 5', 'Item 6'] }
]

// Create a ref to track the open/closed state of each section
// Set all sections to be closed initially
const openSections = ref(Array(sections.length).fill(false))

// Function to toggle a section's open/closed state
const toggleSection = (index: number) => {
  openSections.value[index] = !openSections.value[index]
}
</script>

<style scoped>
/* Add your styles here */
</style>

Key Points:

  1. State Management with ref: The openSections array tracks whether each section is open (true) or closed (false). It’s initialized with all sections set to false (closed).
  2. Toggling State: When the user clicks on a section, the toggleSection function toggles the open/closed state.
  3. Conditional Rendering: The <ul> element containing the dropdown content is only rendered if the corresponding openSections[index] is true.

Integration with Your Sidebar:

If you have a more complex sidebar or need to control the initial open/closed state of specific items, you can extend this pattern by:

  • Using nested ref structures for deeply nested dropdowns.
  • Setting different initial states for specific dropdowns.

This approach ensures that the side navigation dropdowns remain closed initially and only open when explicitly toggled by the user.

vue

  <li v-for="person in people" :key="person.email" class="flex justify-between gap-x-6 py-5">
    <div class="flex min-w-0 gap-x-4">
      <img class="h-12 w-12 flex-none rounded-full bg-gray-50" :src="person.imageUrl" alt="" />
      <div class="min-w-0 flex-auto">

        <p class="mt-1 truncate text-xs leading-5 text-gray-500">{{ person.email }}</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="hidden shrink-0 sm:flex sm:flex-col sm:items-end">
      <p class="text-sm leading-6 text-gray-900">{{ person.role }}</p>
      <p v-if="person.lastSeen" class="mt-1 text-xs leading-5 text-gray-500">
        Last seen <time :datetime="person.lastSeenDateTime">{{ person.lastSeen }}</time>
      </p>
      <div v-else class="mt-1 flex items-center gap-x-1.5">
        <div class="flex-none rounded-full bg-emerald-500/20 p-1">

Key Points:

  • Add bg-white to the <ul> element: This ensures that the background of the list is white.
  • Maintain the existing divide-y divide-gray-100: These classes control the dividing lines between list items and should work well with the white background.
  • Child Elements: Ensure that no unwanted background colors are applied to the child elements, such as the image or any text blocks.

This approach gives the entire list a clean white background while preserving the layout and styling.

You said:
Is it possible for me to add hyperlinks to the names or logos?
ChatGPT said:

Unfortunately, images themselves cannot have clickable hyperlinks directly embedded. However, there are a few alternatives for making parts of your image interactive:

1. Use HTML Image Maps:

You can define clickable areas (like shapes or polygons) on an image using HTML image maps. This allows you to link different regions of the image to specific URLs.

Here's a basic example:

html
<img src="path/to/your-image.png" alt="Open Source Tree" usemap="#openSourceMap" />

<map name="openSourceMap">
  <area shape="rect" coords="34,44,270,350" href="https://www.linux.org" alt="Linux" />
  <area shape="rect" coords="290,172,333,250" href="https://www.python.org" alt="Python" />
  <!-- Add more areas for different logos -->
</map>
  • shape: Specifies the shape of the clickable area (rect, circle, poly).
  • coords: Coordinates defining the area. For example, a rectangle might have x1, y1, x2, y2.
  • href: The URL to link to.

2. Overlay HTML/CSS Elements on the Image:

You can position HTML elements like icons, logos, or text on top of the image using CSS. Each of these elements can have its own hyperlink.

Example:

html
<div class="tree-container">
  <img src="path/to/your-image.png" alt="Open Source Tree" />

  <!-- Position these links over the image -->
  <a href="https://www.linux.org" class="logo-link" style="top: 50px; left: 100px;">
    <img src="path/to/linux-logo.png" alt="Linux" />
  </a>

  <a href="https://www.python.org" class="logo-link" style="top: 150px; left: 200px;">
    <img src="path/to/python-logo.png" alt="Python" />
  </a>
</div>

<style>
.tree-container {
  position: relative;
  display: inline-block;
}

.logo-link {
  position: absolute;
}
</style>

This allows you to have interactive elements that align with specific parts of the image.

3. Use SVG with Hyperlinks:

If you convert your image to SVG format, you can directly embed hyperlinks within the SVG file using the <a> element.

Example:

xml
<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="500" height="500">
  <a href="https://www.linux.org" target="_blank">
    <image x="10" y="10" width="100" height="100" href="path/to/linux-logo.svg" />
  </a>
  <a href="https://www.python.org" target="_blank">
    <image x="120" y="10" width="100" height="100" href="path/to/python-logo.svg" />
  </a>
</svg>

This method is particularly useful for maintaining vector quality and precision.

Conclusion:

While you cannot directly embed hyperlinks into static image files like PNG or JPEG, you can achieve similar functionality using HTML image maps, overlaying HTML/CSS elements, or converting the image into SVG format. Each of these approaches can be customized to create an interactive experience.

Why are the p-values in the following notation?: 3.340202e-08
ChatGPT said:

The p-values are displayed in scientific notation (like 3.340202e-08) because they are very small numbers, and R automatically uses this format to make it easier to read and avoid displaying a long string of zeros.

Understanding Scientific Notation:

  • The value 3.340202e-08 means 3.340202 × 10^(-8), which is 0.00000003340202. In other words, the e-08 indicates that the decimal point should be moved 8 places to the left.

Converting to Regular Decimal Notation:

If you want the p-values in a more standard decimal format (e.g., 0.00000003340202) or rounded to a more interpretable number (like 0.000), you can do the following:

Option 1: Use format() to Convert the P-Values

You can use the format() function with scientific = FALSE to convert p-values to regular decimal notation:

r
p_value_formatted <- format(p_value, scientific = FALSE)

Option 2: Round the P-Values for Better Readability

You can also round the p-values to a certain number of decimal places using round():

r
p_value_rounded <- round(p_value, digits = 6)  # Adjust digits as needed

Updating the Code to Round P-Values:

If you want to round all p-values in your table to 3 decimal places for easier interpretation, update the relevant part of your code like this:

r
results_df <- rbind(results_df, data.frame(IV = iv, Standardized_Estimate = estimate, P_Value = round(p_value, 3)))

Final Output Example:

If the original p-value was 3.340202e-08, rounding it to 3 decimal places would display it as 0.000.

This approach allows you to present the results in a more reader-friendly way, depending on your reporting needs.

Incorporating This into Your Existing Code:

You can update your loop or models to include this formatting when you store the results:

r
results_df <- rbind(results_df, data.frame(IV = iv,

ChatGPT said:

Given that your anyrecid_numeric outcome is a numeric proportion ranging from 0 to 0.55, the binomial family may not be the most appropriate choice for modeling this type of data.

Why Binomial May Not Be Appropriate:

  • The binomial family is typically used for binary outcomes (0 or 1) or for modeling success/failure outcomes based on a proportion with a known number of trials (e.g., number of successes out of total attempts). Your outcome appears to be a continuous proportion, not a binary variable.

More Suitable Options for Proportion Data:

  1. Beta Regression: A beta regression is often the preferred choice for modeling continuous proportions between 0 and 1 (exclusive). The beta distribution is flexible and can model a wide range of shapes suitable for proportion data.

  2. Quasi-Binomial or Gaussian (Linear) Model: If your data are closer to continuous proportions (and not strictly confined to 0 or 1), you might consider using a Gaussian (linear) model or a quasi-binomial model.

Recommended Approach: Beta Regression

To fit a beta regression model in R, you can use the betareg package:

Implementing a Standard Linear Regression with Robust Standard Errors

Here’s how you can run the analysis using a standard linear regression with robust standard errors:

r

Full Updated Code:

r
# Required libraries
library(sandwich)
library(lmtest)

# List of independent variables

  "yls_total", "spep_total", "pop_score", "target_dosage", "target_duration", 
  "total_quality_measures_received", "total_pts_amount_of_service", "total_pts_risk_level",

cohort_summary$target_dosage <- scale(cohort_summary$target_dosage)
cohort_summary$target_duration <- scale(cohort_summary$target_duration)

estimate2 <- round(robust_se2[2, 1], 2)
p_value2 <- round(robust_se2[2, 4], 2)
results_df <- rbind(results_df, data.frame(IV = "spep_total", Standardized_Estimate = estimate2, P_Value = sprintf("p = %.2f", p_value2)))

# Model 3: pop_score
model3 <- lm(anyrecid_numeric ~ pop_score, data = cohort_summary)

# Model 4: target_dosage

What Is the Standardized Estimate?

A standardized estimate (also called a beta coefficient) represents the effect of the predictor in units of standard deviations, making it easier to compare the relative strength of predictors across different models.

How to Calculate the Standardized Estimate:

  1. Fit the Model on Standardized Data: If both the dependent variable (anyrecid_numeric) and the predictor (yls_total) are standardized (mean-centered and scaled to have unit variance), then the coefficient obtained from the regression is the standardized estimate.

  2. Manually Calculate the Standardized Estimate: You can calculate the standardized estimate using this formula:

    Standardized Estimate=β^×(σpredictorσoutcome)\text{Standardized Estimate} = \hat{\beta} \times \left(\frac{\sigma_{\text{predictor}}}{\sigma_{\text{outcome}}}\right)Standardized Estimate=β^​×(σoutcome​σpredictor​​)

    Where:

    • β^\hat{\beta}β^​ is the unstandardized coefficient from your model.
    • σpredictor\sigma_{\text{predictor}}σpredictor​ is the standard deviation of the predictor (yls_total).
    • σoutcome\sigma_{\text{outcome}}σoutcome​ is the standard deviation of the outcome (anyrecid_numeric).

Steps to Obtain the Standardized Estimate:

  1. Extract the Unstandardized Coefficient:

    r
    model1 <- lm(anyrecid_numeric ~ yls_total, data = cohort_summary)
unstandardized_estimate <- coef(model1)["yls_total"]

  2. Calculate the Standard Deviations:

    r
    sd_predictor <- sd(cohort_summary$yls_total)
sd_outcome <- sd(cohort_summary$anyrecid_numeric)

  3. Calculate the Standardized Estimate:

    r
    standardized_estimate <- unstandardized_estimate * (sd_predictor / sd_outcome)
print(standardized_estimate)

Example Calculation:

Suppose the unstandardized coefficient for yls_total is 0.03, and the standard deviations of the predictor and outcome are:

  • sd_predictor = 1 (after scaling, the standard deviation is 1).
  • sd_outcome = 0.13.

The standardized estimate would be:

Standardized Estimate=0.03×(10.13)=0.23\text{Standardized Estimate} = 0.03 \times \left(\frac{1}{0.13}\right) = 0.23Standardized Estimate=0.03×(0.131​)=0.23

Alternative Approach: Using the lm.beta Package

If you want a quick way to extract standardized coefficients, you can use the lm.beta package:

r
install.packages("lm.beta")
